A strong low pressure system will bring a large amount of warm and moist air over Western Alaska starting Monday into Wednesday. Areas can expect a mix of snow and freezing rain with this system as it moves north. Freezing rain chances will reach as far north as Kivalina by Tuesday afternoon. Ice accumulations of up to one tenth of an inch are possible, with snow amounts ranging from 2 to 5 inches where Winter Storm Warnings are not in effect. Higher snow totals are likely in the Bendeleben Mountains and where warnings are in effect.
The system will also bring strong southeast winds gusting as high as 50 mph to the West Coast and to hills near the coast from Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. This will cause sea levels to rise 1 to 2 feet south of the Bering Strait on Tuesday and Wednesday. While flooding of infrastructure is not expected, these strong winds may cause water to be pushed on top of the sea ice making travel difficult.
Residents should stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at www.weather.gov/afg and prepare for a stormy start to the week.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 12 at 5:44AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary: A series of storms will allow an atmospheric river to set up over Bristol Bay and the Alaska Peninsula starting today and continuing through Wednesday. Total precipitation amounts (liquid) of 0.75 to 1.5 inches are expected along the Alaska Peninsula between King Salmon and Port Heiden, and also in northern Bristol Bay, north and west of Dillingham. High end amounts near 3 inches are possible. Precipitation type will begin as snow today before transitioning to rain for much of the area due to strong winds and temperatures in the mid 30s. A west to east transition to snow is expected on Tuesday. Areas that stay colder could see over a foot of heavy snow through Thursday morning. Rain on snow may also produce ponding and hazardous travel conditions.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 12 at 5:37AM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A strong low pressure system will move into Bristol Bay during the day on Monday. This system will bring a large amount of warm and moist air over Western Alaska starting Monday into Tuesday. Areas can expect a mix of snow and freezing rain with this system as it moves north. Freezing rain chances will reach as far north as Kivalina by Tuesday afternoon. Ice accumulations of up to one tenth of an inch are posssible, with snow amounts ranging from 2 to 5 inches where Winter Storm Warnings are not in effect. Higher snow totals are likely in the Bendeleben Mountains and where warnings are in effect.
The system will also bring strong southeast winds gusting as high as 50 mph to the West Coast and to hills near the coast from Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. This will cause sea levels to rise 1 to 2 feet south of the Bering Strait on Tuesday and Wednesday. While flooding of infrastructure is not expected, these strong winds may cause water to be pushed on top of the sea ice making travel difficult.
Residents should stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at www.weather.gov/afg and prepare for a stormy start to the week.
